title: For Sale:  Nariakari Arisaka Rifle type 99
postcontent:
The Arisaka Rifle was designed by Colonel Nariakira Arisaka 1852–1915.
The rifles were used heavily everywhere the Imperial Japanese Army fought. 
This is a very good Arisaka Type 99 Bolt action Rifle in 7.7 x58 mm Calibre.
It has all original woodwork and metal work with nice patina throughout.
the barrel's cleaning rod in it's place. It has the correct 2 part wood stock 
in nice condition and is complete with Anti Aircraft sights which
were fitted to these weapons when the threat of the invasion of Japan was imminent.
Each Japanese rifle was marked with the symbol of either the arsenal 
of manufacture or the arsenal that supervised the manufacturing subcontractor. 
This mark can be found on the left side of the receiver at the end of the rifle
serial number. Rifles manufactured by a commercial subcontractor bear the 
subcontractor's mark to the right of the supervising arsenal's mark.
This Rifle was made in Nagoya Arsenal among the years 1923 to 1945 
as indicated in The left side of the breech stamped with serial number 
The folding sights are graduated and have flip down horizontal wings
on a ladder type sight. It is also fitted with an original rare heavy duty
sling made of stiff sand coloured material. At the end of WW2, one of the 
final standing orders of the Imperial Army was to file off the Emperor's family
Chrysanthemum insignia, or 'Mon', from each of the rifles, thereby preventing 
the dishonour of surrendering the symbol. This rifle has had the Chrysanthemum
'mon' insignia removed contemporarily in compliance with the Imperial order. 
At the top of the Barrel has stamped in Japanese Characters  99 type.
The breech housing is stamped with Japanese script mark. Price for this excellent weapon with rare anti-aircraft sights is $1200.00. This Rifle is a "Rare Avis" in conservation.This rifle will be sell independently.
Also will sell independently of the rifle 20 rounds new in their box, Norma Jap (original for this weapon) caliber 7.7 x 58, 174 grains SP precision Ammunition at $150.00.

title: For Sale:  Steyr M1895 8x56R
postcontent:
The Steyr M1895 rifle, also known as Steyr-Mannlicher M95 straight pull rifle, was developed by famous Austrian arms designer Ferdinand Ritter Von Mannlicher. Based on his previous M1890 design, this rifle was manufactured in Austro-Hungarian Empire at state arms factories in Steyr (Austria) and Budapest (Hungary). More than 3 million of M95 rifles were produced between 1895 and 1918. This rifle was issued to Austro-Hungarian army, and, after the fall of the Empire, to the Austrian and Hungarian armies.  Since 1930 Austria converted most of the M95 rifles to the more powerful 8x56R M30 ammunition, using the same Mannlicher en bloc clips. These rifles were designated as M95/30, and marked with the letter "S" on the receiver ring. Hungary started to convert their rifles to the same 8x56R ammunition in 1931, with the upgraded rifles being marked with the letter "H" on the receiver ring. Many of the M95 rifles were used during the Word War 2 by the Hungarian, Bulgarian and Italian armies, as well as by some German police forces.
Steyr Mannlicher M95 bolt has a separate head with two frontal locking lugs; bolt head was inserted into the bolt body from the front. Bolt body had internal spiral-shaped ribs, with matching spiral-shaped cuts in the tail of the bolt head. These ribs and cuts forced the bolt head to rotate on the pull of the bolt body, locking and unlocking the action. Box magazine contained five rounds in en bloc clips; as the magazine emptied, the clips were ejected from the opening at the bottom of the magazine. Non-empty clips could be removed from the top with the bolt open, by depressing the clip catch inside the triggerguard. One specific feature of this system was that the clip has specific "top" and "bottom" sides, and could not be loaded into the rifle upside down. The safety was located at the rear left side of the bolt. Large ear-shaped cocking handle at the rear of the bolt served as a manual cocking handle, to re-cock the action without operating the bolt. M95 rifles were issued with detachable knife bayonets. Other than basic rifle, M95 also was issued as Stutzen (short rifle or carbine, with bayonet lug), and slightly shorter cavalry carbine (without bayonet lug).
These rifles are generally considered as a reasonably strong and accurate, but somewhat sensitive to mud and dirt, as most others military straight pull bolt action rifles. There were several downsides, inherent to these rifles. The straight pull bolt lacked the powerful initial extraction, provided by most rotating bolt actions. The en block clip loading system does not allow the partially full magazine to be refilled without removing the non-empty clip first. The use of rimmed ammunition resulted in the non-symmetric clip which could be inserted into the action only with one side down; upper side of the clip has stamped serrations to hold it while loading (this particular problem was cured in Italian Carcano rifles, which used rimless ammunition, and symmetric clips).

This rifle also includes 200 rounds of ammunition.

If you're looking to add a nice rifle to your militaria collection, this rifle will fill that bill.

title: For Sale/Trade:  BNIC AR15 in 6.8 SPCII, MagPul, Trijicon, + 640 rounds of Ammo.
postcontent:
I’ve never spent more cash building an AR15 up to this point. This is a Yankee Hill Machine complete Specter Black Diamond upper on top of a YHM lower that includes a $230 Timney drop-in 3lb trigger group and $260 MagPul UBR stock that I‘ve upgraded with their $25 Aluminum Strike Plate and $20 Enhanced Rubber Buttpad. There’s also an ambidextrous selector and enhanced bolt release. The upper has a Young Manufacturing bolt carrier group (the best BCGs on the market) and Bravo Company Gunfighter charging handle. The MAID grip, AFG and multi-color XTM rail panels are all from MagPul and the BUIS are YHM’s low profile Q.D.S. sights.

The optic is a $765 1.25-4x24Trijicon TR21 AccuPoint. This Trijicon combines the best of ACOGs and zoom scopes. Like the ACOG, its dual-illuminated triangle aiming point glows at night from tritium, and during the day from the fiber-optic system. There is also a feature for dimming the fiber optic in really bright days. Advanced, multilayer coated optics permit excellent light transmission without parallax and the quick-focus eye-piece gives users rapid clarity adjustment. It also has a wider field of view and longer eye-relief that accommodates large caliber rifles and being mounted farther forward on flat top uppers. It’s mounted with a $100 Burris PEPR one piece mount.

Included with this package is the $200 Pelican 1700 case shown, $45 VTAC sling, 14 magazines and 640 rounds of fresh factory ammo. All but 4 of the magazines are brand new, one is a $50 Barrett that holds a full 30 rounds, three are 25 round $45 Precision Reflex, one is a 10 round $38 also by Precision Reflex, seven are cheaper 25 round and two are 10 round by C-Products. Each 25 round mag has a MagPul Ranger Plate installed. That’s over $360 in mags alone. For ammo there are 24 boxes of Hornady 110gr V-Max, three boxes of Double Tap 110gr Rifle Defense, three boxes of Remington 115gr HPBT. There is more than $800 in ammo here which saves you the trouble of hunting some down (if there is any actually available).

I have more than $2900 in the firearm and optics alone, another $360 in mags, $250 in the case and sling and $800 in ammo. That’s more than $4300 invested all together but I’ll take $3400 for everything. THE SCOPE HAS NOT BEEN ZEROED SO THAT WILL NEED TO BE DONE BY THE PURCHASER.
